
Node.js backend with PostgreSQL

1. Update & Upgrade System Packages
Always start by updating system packages.

sudo apt update

sudo apt upgrade -y

Install Node.js & NPM
Use NodeSource to install the latest LTS (as per project requirement) version.

curl -fsSL https://deb.nodesource.com/setup_20.x | sudo -E bash -

sudo apt install -y nodejs

Check version (must be ≥ 20.6):

node -v

npm -v

Install PM2 (Process Manager for Node.js)
sudo npm install -g pm2

pm2 -v

Install PostgreSQL 16.4 ( as per project requirement)
sudo sh -c ‘echo “deb http://apt.postgresql.org/pub/repos/apt $(lsb_release -cs)-pgdg main” > /etc/apt/sources.list.d/pgdg.list’

wget --quiet -O - https://www.postgresql.org/media/keys/ACCC4CF8.asc | sudo apt-key add -

sudo apt update

Install PostgreSQL 16:

sudo apt install -y postgresql-16 postgresql-contrib-16

psql --version

Install Nginx

sudo apt install -y nginx

sudo systemctl enable nginx

sudo systemctl start nginx

Configure PostgreSQL Database & User
CREATE DATABASE localdb;

ALTER USER postgres WITH PASSWORD ‘postgres’;

GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON DATABASE localdb TO postgres;

Exit:

\q

exit

Project Setup
mkdir travelhero

cd travelhero

git init

git remote add origin https://github.com/Rajsekar-s-Organisation/travelhero.git

git checkout -b main

git pull origin main

Store credentials:
git config credential.helper store

1.Check if Credential Helper is Set
git config credential.helper or git config --global credential.helper

If it shows: store (then Git will save credentials after your next push/pull.)

Where Credentials Are Stored
cat ~/.git-credentials

Check Git Username & Email
git config user.name

git config user.email

Set Username & Email (if not already set)
git config user.name “Your Name”
git config user.email "your@email.com"



Install dependencies:
npm install

Run locally: npm start

Run with PM2 (Production)
pm2 start npm --name travelhero-backend – start

pm2 startup

pm2 save

pm2 logs travelhero-backend



Nginx setup:
sudo rm /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/default

sudo nano /etc/nginx/sites-available/travelhero

server {

listen 80;

server_name 82n.xyz;

location / {

proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:3000;

proxy_http_version 1.1;

proxy_set_header Upgrade $http_upgrade;

proxy_set_header Connection ‘upgrade’;

proxy_set_header Host $host;

proxy_cache_bypass $http_upgrade;

}

}

sudo ln -s /etc/nginx/sites-available/travelhero /etc/nginx/sites-enabled/

sudo nginx -t

sudo systemctl restart nginx

Add domain and IP in Route53

Or use certificate manger

sudo certbot --nginx -d 82n.xyz -d www.82n.xyz



DB setup for separate database roles (as per needs)

Admin Role
Full privileges (create, alter, drop, grant, etc.).

Used only by DB admin (not the application).

– Logged in as postgres superuser

CREATE ROLE travelhero_admin WITH LOGIN PASSWORD ‘StrongAdminPass’;

GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON DATABASE localdb TO travelhero_admin;

2. Application Role
Can read/write data but cannot drop database or create new roles.

This is what your Node.js backend should use.

CREATE ROLE travelhero_app WITH LOGIN PASSWORD ‘StrongAppPass’;

– Grant privileges on existing DB

GRANT CONNECT ON DATABASE localdb TO travelhero_app;

– Switch to db

\c localdb

– Give permissions on public schema

GRANT USAGE ON SCHEMA public TO travelhero_app;

– Allow CRUD on tables

GRANT SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA public TO travelhero_app;

– Allow sequences (for SERIAL IDs)

GRANT USAGE, SELECT, UPDATE ON ALL SEQUENCES IN SCHEMA public TO travelhero_app;

3. Read-Only Role (Optional)
Can only run SELECT queries.

Useful for analytics/reporting.

CREATE ROLE travelhero_readonly WITH LOGIN PASSWORD ‘ReadOnlyPass’;

\c localdb

GRANT CONNECT ON DATABASE localdb TO travelhero_readonly;

GRANT USAGE ON SCHEMA public TO travelhero_readonly;

GRANT SELECT ON ALL TABLES IN SCHEMA public TO travelhero_readonly;
